This project created and deployed soft end-effectors and manipulator systems for delicate deep sea manipulation and sampling. This has included the development of new soft robot hands, arms, and associated power and control infrastructure. These soft robots have been deployed around the world?s oceans, successfully sampling organisms that would elude the grasp of, or be damaged by, more traditional manipulators. 

The project focused on the following topics:

Compliant yet dexterous end-effectors capable of non-destructive interactions with deep-sea organisms;
Fabrication methods, including in situ fabrication methods, for these soft manipulators;
Ultra-delicate end-effectors that enable grasps on gelatinous organisms (that would be impossible to grasp and sample with existing hardware);
Exploration of deterministic vs random contact for delicate grasping;
Soft robot arms to control motion of the compliant end-effectors; and
A robust seawater engine to modularly power and control the arm/hands.




Multiple graduate students and a postdoctoral researcher have been partially funded by this program. Through this program, these researchers have had a significant opportunities for both lab-based engineering design as well as field work on various expeditions we have been involved with. The project participants have interacted with numerous researchers outside of engineering ? in particular with marine biologists and ocean scientists. Two of these students have since graduated, and one has recently accepted a faculty position in Mechanical Engineering.

Several publications and presentations are either under review, in press, or published/public. We have also participated in an exhibition in the American Museum of Natural History in New York that describes our efforts to create delicate robots for deep sea sampling.

